+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LTiDe4SXx4vMfe9FWJaKkR","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the structured code review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: In-Memory Task Queue System\n\n## HIGH PRIORITY: Bugs and Missing Required Functionality\n\n### H1. `get()` ordering violates Phase 4 spec -- priority should take precedence over availability time\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 158-169\n\nThe Phase 4 spec says: *\"When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\"* However, the current comparator orders by **priority first**, then availability time, then FIFO:\n\n```typescript\nif (\n  bestTask === null ||\n  task.priority < bestTask.priority ||                          // priority first\n  (task.priority === bestTask.priority &&\n    task.availableAt.getTime() < bestTask.availableAt.getTime()) || // then availableAt\n  (task.priority === bestTask.priority &&\n    task.availableAt.getTime() === bestTask.availableAt.getTime() &&\n    bestIndex > i)                                               // then FIFO\n)\n```\n\nThe question is whether the spec intends \"availability time, then priority, then FIFO\" as the *global* ordering or only *among delayed tasks that became available simultaneously*. Reading the spec literally, it says \"when multiple delayed tasks become available **simultaneously**\" -- meaning availability time is a tiebreaker among tasks that are all ready, which would mean priority-first is the correct global behavior. The current code does use availability time as a secondary sort within same-priority, which breaks FIFO for same-priority non-delayed tasks that were added at very slightly different `Date.now()` values. Consider: two tasks added at priority 5 with no delay, but `new Date()` yields times 1ms apart. The second one would never sort first even though FIFO should apply. In practice this is unlikely since `Date.now()` granularity often yields the same value, but it is an inconsistency.\n\n**Severity:** Medium-High. In realistic usage this rarely manifests, but it can break FIFO for same-priority, non-delayed tasks when `Date.now()` ticks between adds.\n\n### H2. `cancel()` does not remove processing tasks from the queue array\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 428-443\n\nWhen a **processing** task is cancelled, its status changes to `'cancelled'`, but the task ID is **not** removed from the `queues` array. The comment says \"Remove from queue if pending,\" but the splice runs unconditionally for any task found in the array. However, a more subtle bug exists: `getActiveCount()` (line 370-381) counts tasks with `status === 'processing'` by iterating over the queue array. After cancellation, the cancelled task still sits in the array but with `'cancelled'` status, so `getActiveCount` correctly does not count it. This means the dangling ID is harmless for correctness but causes a **memory/performance leak**: the queue array accumulates dead entries that are scanned every `get()` and `size()` call. Over many cancel operations, this degrades `get()` from O(n) where n = pending tasks to O(n + cancelled).\n\nThe comment implies an intent to only remove pending tasks, but the code actually removes the task unconditionally (if found). So for processing tasks, the `indexOf` will still find and remove them, meaning the actual behavior is fine. Wait -- let me re-read:\n\n```typescript\ntask.status = 'cancelled';\n// Remove from queue if pending\nconst queue = this.queues.get(task.queueName);\nif (queue) {\n  const idx = queue.indexOf(taskId);\n  if (idx !== -1) queue.splice(idx, 1);\n}\n```\n\nThe splice runs **regardless** of whether the task was pending or processing. So the ID is always removed from the queue array. This is actually correct behavior. The comment is just misleading. No bug here after all.\n\n### H3. `use()` without a queue name only registers middleware for `'default'` queue\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 500-518\n\n```typescript\nuse(queueName: string, middleware: Middleware): void;\nuse(middleware: Middleware): void;\nuse(queueNameOrMiddleware: string | Middleware, middleware?: Middleware): void {\n  let name: string;\n  let mw: Middleware;\n\n  if (typeof queueNameOrMiddleware === 'string') {\n    name = queueNameOrMiddleware;\n    mw = middleware!;\n  } else {\n    name = DEFAULT_QUEUE;  // <-- always 'default'\n    mw = queueNameOrMiddleware;\n  }\n```\n\nThe single-argument `use(middleware)` overload registers middleware only on the `'default'` queue. This is not necessarily a \"global\" middleware mechanism. A developer calling `queue.use(myLogger)` expecting it to apply to all queues would be surprised. The Phase 11 spec says \"Middleware functions can be registered per queue,\" so strictly speaking this is spec-compliant, but the API shape of a no-queue-name overload strongly implies \"apply to all queues.\" At minimum, the behavior should be documented or the no-argument overload should be removed to avoid confusion.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. API design issue that will confuse users.\n\n### H4. `process()` does not call `complete()` on success\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 530-552\n\n```typescript\nasync process<T = unknown>(task: Task<T>): Promise<void> {\n  const middlewares = this.middlewareStacks.get(task.queueName) ?? [];\n  const handler = this.handlers.get(task.queueName);\n\n  // ... runs middleware + handler ...\n\n  try {\n    await next();\n  } catch (err) {\n    const message = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);\n    this.fail(task.id, message);\n    throw err;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nWhen the middleware pipeline and handler complete **successfully**, `process()` does not call `this.complete(task.id)`. The task remains in `'processing'` status after `process()` returns without error. The caller must manually call `complete()` after `await process()`. This is asymmetric: on failure the task is automatically moved to failed/retry state, but on success the caller must remember to call `complete()`. This is a likely source of bugs for consumers.\n\n**Severity:** High. Tasks will remain stuck in `'processing'` status after successful processing unless the caller explicitly calls `complete()`. This is at odds with how `process()` handles the failure path automatically.\n\n### H5. `process()` calls `fail()` then re-throws -- caller gets exception even though task was already handled\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 546-551\n\n```typescript\ntry {\n  await next();\n} catch (err) {\n  const message = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);\n  this.fail(task.id, message);\n  throw err;  // <-- re-throws after fail()\n}\n```\n\nAfter `fail()` handles the task (either requeueing with backoff or moving to DLQ), the error is re-thrown to the caller. If the caller catches this and also calls `fail()`, a double-fail occurs, which throws `\"Cannot fail task in status: pending\"` (if retried) or `\"Cannot fail task in status: failed\"` (if DLQ'd). The re-throw is acceptable as a design choice, but it creates a footgun: any process-loop code wrapping `process()` in try/catch must be careful not to call `fail()` again.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. Design inconsistency that can cause secondary exceptions.\n\n### H6. Dead letter queue: `retryDeadLetterTask` does not preserve failure count\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 265-291\n\nPhase 6 spec: *\"Dead-lettered tasks should retain their error information and a count of how many times they failed.\"*\n\nThe `Task` type uses `attempts` to track execution count, but there is no separate field for total failure count. When `retryDeadLetterTask` is called, `attempts` is reset to 0 (line 281):\n\n```typescript\ntask.attempts = 0;\n```\n\nThis erases the history of how many times the task failed. If a task was retried from the DLQ multiple times, there would be no record of cumulative failures. The spec says dead-lettered tasks should retain \"a count of how many times they failed,\" implying a persistent `failCount` or equivalent that survives DLQ retry.\n\n**Severity:** High. Missing required functionality per Phase 6 spec.\n\n### H7. Circular dependency detection is incomplete\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 314-342\n\nThe `detectCircularDeps` method only runs DFS starting from the **new task**. Consider this scenario:\n\n1. Add task A (no deps)\n2. Add task B (depends on A)\n3. Add task C (depends on B)\n\nNow we want to detect: if task D is added with `dependencies: [C]`, and somehow A depended on D, that would be a cycle. But since A has no dependencies on D (A was created first), no cycle exists -- which is correct.\n\nThe real limitation is that you can never create a true cycle in this system because dependencies must reference **already existing** tasks. A -> B -> C -> A is impossible to construct because when adding C with `dependencies: [B]`, A already exists without deps on C. The cycle detection is therefore never triggered in practice for the actual API. The test at line 331-360 acknowledges this:\n\n```typescript\nit('should reject circular dependencies', () => {\n  // ... test doesn't actually create a cycle\n});\nit('should detect indirect circular dependencies', () => {\n  // ... test doesn't actually test a cycle either\n});\n```\n\nBoth tests pass vacuously -- they never assert that a cycle is detected. The circular dependency detection code is dead code that can never fire given the current API design.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. The spec requires \"Circular dependencies (direct or indirect) must be detected and rejected at task-creation time.\" The detection code exists but is unreachable because the API cannot construct cycles. The tests do not verify this functionality. If the system were ever extended to allow modifying a task's dependencies, the detection would be needed.\n\n### H8. `getActiveCount()` scans the queue array, which excludes cancelled/completed tasks already spliced out\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 370-381\n\n```typescript\ngetActiveCount(queueName?: string): number {\n  const name = queueName ?? DEFAULT_QUEUE;\n  const queue = this.queues.get(name);\n  if (!queue) return 0;\n\n  let count = 0;\n  for (const id of queue) {\n    const task = this.tasks.get(id);\n    if (task && task.status === 'processing') count++;\n  }\n  return count;\n}\n```\n\nThis iterates over the queue array. However, tasks that were moved to the DLQ have been `splice`d out of the queue array (line 252). If a task is in `'processing'` status and has not been spliced out, it will be counted. But the real issue is: after `cancel()` for a processing task, the task is spliced out of the queue array but still has status `'processing'` at the point of cancellation -- wait, no, `cancel()` sets status to `'cancelled'` first (line 435), then splices. So after cancel, it would not be counted. This is fine.\n\nHowever, there is a subtle correctness issue with concurrency control: when `get()` checks `getActiveCount` (line 137), it only scans the current queue's array. But if a task is processing and then its ID is removed from the queue array (e.g., by some future code path), the concurrency slot would be silently freed. Currently, the only code path that removes processing tasks from the array is `cancel()`, which also changes status. So this is not a bug today but is fragile.\n\n**Severity:** Low. Not a current bug, but the architecture of counting active tasks by scanning the queue array rather than a dedicated counter is fragile.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM PRIORITY: Significant Design Issues\n\n### M1. Duplicated task construction code in `add()`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 80-127\n\nThe `add()` method has two nearly identical code blocks for constructing a task -- one for when dependencies exist and one for when they don't. The only difference is:\n- The dependency path pre-generates a UUID for cycle detection\n- The no-dependency path generates UUID inline\n\nThis can be consolidated into a single code path:\n\n```typescript\nconst taskId = randomUUID();\nif (dependencies.length > 0) {\n  this.detectCircularDeps(taskId, dependencies);\n}\nconst task: Task<T> = { id: taskId, /* ... */ dependencies: [...dependencies] };\n// ...\n```\n\n**Severity:** Medium. Code duplication increases maintenance burden and risk of divergence.\n\n### M2. Queue array grows unboundedly with completed/failed tasks\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`\n\nThe `queues` Map stores arrays of task IDs. When tasks are completed or failed (and retried), they remain in the array. The `get()` method (line 150) skips non-pending tasks with `continue`, and `size()` (line 188) only counts pending ones. But the arrays never shrink (except for DLQ moves via `moveToDeadLetterQueue` and cancellations). Over time, with many completed tasks, the arrays grow and `get()` degrades because it must iterate past all completed/processing entries.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. Performance degradation over time in long-running systems.\n\n### M3. `complete()` does not remove task from queue array\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 201-213\n\nWhen a task is completed, its status changes but the task ID remains in the queue array. This contributes to the unbounded growth issue in M2. Compare with `cancel()` and `moveToDeadLetterQueue()`, which both splice the ID out.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. Inconsistency with cancel/DLQ paths and contributes to performance issue M2.\n\n### M4. `getDependencyStatus` returns `'unknown'` cast as `TaskStatus` for deleted dependencies\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 344-355\n\n```typescript\nreturn {\n  dependency: depId,\n  status: dep ? dep.status : ('unknown' as TaskStatus),\n};\n```\n\nThe string `'unknown'` is not a valid `TaskStatus` (which is `'pending' | 'processing' | 'completed' | 'failed' | 'cancelled'`). This cast bypasses TypeScript's type safety. If a dependency was cleared from the DLQ via `clearDeadLetterQueue()` (which deletes from `this.tasks`), the status would show as `'unknown'` despite the type saying otherwise.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. Type safety violation that masks a potential runtime issue.\n\n### M5. `cron.ts` `shouldRun` does not handle month boundaries in lastRun check\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/cron.ts`, lines 71-81 and 95-106\n\n```typescript\nif (\n  lastDate === now.getDate() &&\n  lastHour === currentHour &&\n  lastMinute === currentMinute\n) {\n  return false;\n}\n```\n\nThe duplicate-run check only compares day-of-month, hour, and minute. It does not compare the month or year. If `lastRun` was on January 15 at 12:10, and `now` is February 15 at 12:10, the function would incorrectly return `false` (thinking it already ran at this slot), skipping the February occurrence.\n\n**Severity:** High. This is a correctness bug that causes missed cron executions on the same day-of-month in subsequent months.\n\n### M6. `tick()` re-parses cron expressions on every call\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 477-496\n\n```typescript\ntick(now?: Date): Task[] {\n  for (const schedule of this.schedules.values()) {\n    const fields = parseCron(schedule.cronExpression);  // parsed every tick\n```\n\nThe cron expression is already validated and parsed during `addSchedule()` (line 448), but the parsed result is discarded. On every `tick()`, the expression is parsed again. The `Schedule` type should store the parsed `CronFields` to avoid redundant parsing.\n\n**Severity:** Low-Medium. Wasteful but not incorrect.\n\n---\n\n## CONSIDER: Minor Improvements\n\n### C1. `fail()` with `backoffDelay: 0` and `maxRetries: 1` produces `delay = 0 * 2^0 = 0`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, line 224\n\n```typescript\nconst delay = task.backoffDelay * Math.pow(2, task.attempts - 1);\n```\n\nWhen `backoffDelay` is 0, the delay is always 0 regardless of attempt number. This means retries happen immediately with no backoff. This may be intentional for testing, but it could surprise users who set `backoffDelay: 0` expecting \"no delay\" to mean \"don't retry.\" This is a documentation concern.\n\n### C2. Test for Phase 5 retry tracking is non-deterministic\n\n**File:** `/workspace/tests/task-queue.test.ts`, lines 208-230\n\n```typescript\nit('should track attempt count', () => {\n  queue.add('work', { maxRetries: 3, backoffDelay: 1 });\n  const t1 = queue.get()!;\n  expect(t1.attempts).toBe(1);\n  queue.fail(t1.id);\n  let t2 = check();\n  if (!t2) {\n    // still delayed, skip this check   <-- test silently passes without verifying\n  } else {\n    expect(t2.attempts).toBe(2);\n  }\n});\n```\n\nThe test may skip its core assertion if the 1ms backoff has not elapsed. The `if (!t2)` branch silently passes without asserting anything meaningful. This test should use a deterministic approach (e.g., `availableAt` manipulation or `backoffDelay: 0`).\n\n### C3. `clearDeadLetterQueue` deletes tasks from the `tasks` Map, orphaning any references\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 293-302\n\n```typescript\nclearDeadLetterQueue(queueName?: string): void {\n  const name = queueName ?? DEFAULT_QUEUE;\n  const dlq = this.deadLetterQueues.get(name);\n  if (dlq) {\n    for (const id of dlq) {\n      this.tasks.delete(id);\n    }\n    dlq.length = 0;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis deletes the task objects entirely. If any other task has a dependency on a cleared DLQ task, `areDependenciesMet` will return `false` forever (because `this.tasks.get(depId)` returns undefined, line 308-309). The dependent task becomes permanently blocked with no way to unblock it.\n\n### C4. `process()` does not check if the task is actually in `'processing'` status\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, line 530\n\nThe `process()` method accepts any `Task` object and runs the middleware pipeline without verifying the task's status. A caller could pass a completed or cancelled task to `process()`. If it throws, `fail()` would be called and would throw `\"Cannot fail task in status: completed\"`.\n\n### C5. No validation on `maxRetries: 0`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 94, 116\n\nA task with `maxRetries: 0` would immediately fail on first `fail()` call because `attempts` (1 after `get()`) is not less than `maxRetries` (0). The spec says \"default maximum number of retries is 3\" but does not specify behavior for 0. This may be intentional (no retries = immediate failure) but should be documented.\n\n### C6. `shutdown()` does not stop recurring schedules from firing during shutdown\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 477-496 and 564-571\n\nAfter `shutdown()` is called, `tick()` will call `this.add()` which throws `\"Queue system is shutting down.\"` If a consumer has a setInterval calling `tick()`, the interval would start throwing after shutdown begins. The `tick()` method should check `_isShuttingDown` and return an empty array instead of propagating the error.\n\n### C7. Progress listeners are never cleaned up\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, line 33\n\nThe `progressListeners` Map is never cleared. After a task completes, its listeners remain in memory. For long-running systems that process many tasks, this causes a memory leak.\n\n### C8. `size()` counts only `'pending'` tasks, not delayed-but-pending tasks\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 180-191\n\n`size()` counts all pending tasks including those that are delayed (not yet available) and those that are blocked by dependencies. This means `size()` returns a count that does not match the number of tasks that `get()` could actually return. This may be intentional, but it could confuse callers who use `size() > 0` as a proxy for \"there are tasks ready to process.\"\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| ID  | Severity | Phase | Description |\n|-----|----------|-------|-------------|\n| H1  | HIGH     | 4     | FIFO tie-breaking for same-priority tasks broken by sub-ms `availableAt` differences |\n| H4  | HIGH     | 11    | `process()` does not auto-complete on success (asymmetric with auto-fail) |\n| H5  | HIGH     | 11    | `process()` re-throws after `fail()`, risking double-fail by callers |\n| H6  | HIGH     | 6     | No persistent failure count -- DLQ retry resets `attempts` to 0 |\n| H7  | HIGH     | 7     | Circular dependency detection is unreachable; tests are vacuous |\n| M1  | MEDIUM   | 1     | Duplicated task construction code in `add()` |\n| M2  | MEDIUM   | 1     | Queue array grows unboundedly with completed tasks |\n| M3  | MEDIUM   | 5     | `complete()` does not remove task from queue array |\n| M4  | MEDIUM   | 7     | `'unknown'` cast as `TaskStatus` violates type safety |\n| M5  | MEDIUM   | 10    | Cron `shouldRun` lastRun check ignores month/year -- causes missed runs |\n| M6  | MEDIUM   | 10    | Cron expressions re-parsed on every `tick()` |\n| H3  | MEDIUM   | 11    | `use(middleware)` only applies to `'default'` queue despite API shape suggesting global |\n| C1  | CONSIDER | 5     | `backoffDelay: 0` semantics undocumented |\n| C2  | CONSIDER | 5     | Non-deterministic retry test may skip its assertion |\n| C3  | CONSIDER | 6     | `clearDeadLetterQueue` can permanently orphan dependent tasks |\n| C4  | CONSIDER | 11    | `process()` does not validate task status before running |\n| C5  | CONSIDER | 5     | `maxRetries: 0` behavior is implicit, not documented |\n| C6  | CONSIDER | 12    | `tick()` throws during shutdown instead of returning empty |\n| C7  | CONSIDER | 9     | Progress listeners never cleaned up (memory leak) |\n| C8  | CONSIDER | 1     | `size()` includes delayed/blocked tasks that `get()` would not return |"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a3979f1 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 46959\ntool_uses: 21\nduration_ms: 139436</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c224e1c2-6e95-4036-80b3-e4b2caf2cba3","uuid":"fc848930-2887-4914-9d66-175fc1ecefe0","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are a code reviewer. Review the following implementation of an in-memory task queue system. The implementation covers 12 phases:\n\n1. Basic FIFO Queue\n2. Named Queues\n3. Priority\n4. Delayed Tasks\n5. Retry with Backoff\n6. Dead Letter Queue\n7. Task Dependencies\n8. Concurrency Control\n9. Progress and Cancellation\n10. Recurring Tasks\n11. Middleware Pipeline\n12. Graceful Shutdown\n\nRead the following source files and provide a structured code review focusing on:\n- Correctness bugs\n- Missing requirements from the phase specs\n- Edge cases not handled\n- API design issues\n\nFiles to review:\n- /workspace/src/types.ts\n- /workspace/src/cron.ts\n- /workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts\n- /workspace/src/index.ts\n- /workspace/tests/task-queue.test.ts\n\nPhase requirement files for reference:\n- /workspace/phases/phase-01.md through /workspace/phases/phase-12.md\n\nCategorize findings as:\n- HIGH PRIORITY: Bugs or missing required functionality\n- MEDIUM PRIORITY: Significant design issues\n- CONSIDER: Minor improvements\n\nBe thorough and specific. Reference line numbers.","agentId":"a3979f1","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the structured code review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: In-Memory Task Queue System\n\n## HIGH PRIORITY: Bugs and Missing Required Functionality\n\n### H1. `get()` ordering violates Phase 4 spec -- priority should take precedence over availability time\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 158-169\n\nThe Phase 4 spec says: *\"When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\"* However, the current comparator orders by **priority first**, then availability time, then FIFO:\n\n```typescript\nif (\n  bestTask === null ||\n  task.priority < bestTask.priority ||                          // priority first\n  (task.priority === bestTask.priority &&\n    task.availableAt.getTime() < bestTask.availableAt.getTime()) || // then availableAt\n  (task.priority === bestTask.priority &&\n    task.availableAt.getTime() === bestTask.availableAt.getTime() &&\n    bestIndex > i)                                               // then FIFO\n)\n```\n\nThe question is whether the spec intends \"availability time, then priority, then FIFO\" as the *global* ordering or only *among delayed tasks that became available simultaneously*. Reading the spec literally, it says \"when multiple delayed tasks become available **simultaneously**\" -- meaning availability time is a tiebreaker among tasks that are all ready, which would mean priority-first is the correct global behavior. The current code does use availability time as a secondary sort within same-priority, which breaks FIFO for same-priority non-delayed tasks that were added at very slightly different `Date.now()` values. Consider: two tasks added at priority 5 with no delay, but `new Date()` yields times 1ms apart. The second one would never sort first even though FIFO should apply. In practice this is unlikely since `Date.now()` granularity often yields the same value, but it is an inconsistency.\n\n**Severity:** Medium-High. In realistic usage this rarely manifests, but it can break FIFO for same-priority, non-delayed tasks when `Date.now()` ticks between adds.\n\n### H2. `cancel()` does not remove processing tasks from the queue array\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 428-443\n\nWhen a **processing** task is cancelled, its status changes to `'cancelled'`, but the task ID is **not** removed from the `queues` array. The comment says \"Remove from queue if pending,\" but the splice runs unconditionally for any task found in the array. However, a more subtle bug exists: `getActiveCount()` (line 370-381) counts tasks with `status === 'processing'` by iterating over the queue array. After cancellation, the cancelled task still sits in the array but with `'cancelled'` status, so `getActiveCount` correctly does not count it. This means the dangling ID is harmless for correctness but causes a **memory/performance leak**: the queue array accumulates dead entries that are scanned every `get()` and `size()` call. Over many cancel operations, this degrades `get()` from O(n) where n = pending tasks to O(n + cancelled).\n\nThe comment implies an intent to only remove pending tasks, but the code actually removes the task unconditionally (if found). So for processing tasks, the `indexOf` will still find and remove them, meaning the actual behavior is fine. Wait -- let me re-read:\n\n```typescript\ntask.status = 'cancelled';\n// Remove from queue if pending\nconst queue = this.queues.get(task.queueName);\nif (queue) {\n  const idx = queue.indexOf(taskId);\n  if (idx !== -1) queue.splice(idx, 1);\n}\n```\n\nThe splice runs **regardless** of whether the task was pending or processing. So the ID is always removed from the queue array. This is actually correct behavior. The comment is just misleading. No bug here after all.\n\n### H3. `use()` without a queue name only registers middleware for `'default'` queue\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 500-518\n\n```typescript\nuse(queueName: string, middleware: Middleware): void;\nuse(middleware: Middleware): void;\nuse(queueNameOrMiddleware: string | Middleware, middleware?: Middleware): void {\n  let name: string;\n  let mw: Middleware;\n\n  if (typeof queueNameOrMiddleware === 'string') {\n    name = queueNameOrMiddleware;\n    mw = middleware!;\n  } else {\n    name = DEFAULT_QUEUE;  // <-- always 'default'\n    mw = queueNameOrMiddleware;\n  }\n```\n\nThe single-argument `use(middleware)` overload registers middleware only on the `'default'` queue. This is not necessarily a \"global\" middleware mechanism. A developer calling `queue.use(myLogger)` expecting it to apply to all queues would be surprised. The Phase 11 spec says \"Middleware functions can be registered per queue,\" so strictly speaking this is spec-compliant, but the API shape of a no-queue-name overload strongly implies \"apply to all queues.\" At minimum, the behavior should be documented or the no-argument overload should be removed to avoid confusion.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. API design issue that will confuse users.\n\n### H4. `process()` does not call `complete()` on success\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 530-552\n\n```typescript\nasync process<T = unknown>(task: Task<T>): Promise<void> {\n  const middlewares = this.middlewareStacks.get(task.queueName) ?? [];\n  const handler = this.handlers.get(task.queueName);\n\n  // ... runs middleware + handler ...\n\n  try {\n    await next();\n  } catch (err) {\n    const message = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);\n    this.fail(task.id, message);\n    throw err;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nWhen the middleware pipeline and handler complete **successfully**, `process()` does not call `this.complete(task.id)`. The task remains in `'processing'` status after `process()` returns without error. The caller must manually call `complete()` after `await process()`. This is asymmetric: on failure the task is automatically moved to failed/retry state, but on success the caller must remember to call `complete()`. This is a likely source of bugs for consumers.\n\n**Severity:** High. Tasks will remain stuck in `'processing'` status after successful processing unless the caller explicitly calls `complete()`. This is at odds with how `process()` handles the failure path automatically.\n\n### H5. `process()` calls `fail()` then re-throws -- caller gets exception even though task was already handled\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 546-551\n\n```typescript\ntry {\n  await next();\n} catch (err) {\n  const message = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);\n  this.fail(task.id, message);\n  throw err;  // <-- re-throws after fail()\n}\n```\n\nAfter `fail()` handles the task (either requeueing with backoff or moving to DLQ), the error is re-thrown to the caller. If the caller catches this and also calls `fail()`, a double-fail occurs, which throws `\"Cannot fail task in status: pending\"` (if retried) or `\"Cannot fail task in status: failed\"` (if DLQ'd). The re-throw is acceptable as a design choice, but it creates a footgun: any process-loop code wrapping `process()` in try/catch must be careful not to call `fail()` again.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. Design inconsistency that can cause secondary exceptions.\n\n### H6. Dead letter queue: `retryDeadLetterTask` does not preserve failure count\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 265-291\n\nPhase 6 spec: *\"Dead-lettered tasks should retain their error information and a count of how many times they failed.\"*\n\nThe `Task` type uses `attempts` to track execution count, but there is no separate field for total failure count. When `retryDeadLetterTask` is called, `attempts` is reset to 0 (line 281):\n\n```typescript\ntask.attempts = 0;\n```\n\nThis erases the history of how many times the task failed. If a task was retried from the DLQ multiple times, there would be no record of cumulative failures. The spec says dead-lettered tasks should retain \"a count of how many times they failed,\" implying a persistent `failCount` or equivalent that survives DLQ retry.\n\n**Severity:** High. Missing required functionality per Phase 6 spec.\n\n### H7. Circular dependency detection is incomplete\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 314-342\n\nThe `detectCircularDeps` method only runs DFS starting from the **new task**. Consider this scenario:\n\n1. Add task A (no deps)\n2. Add task B (depends on A)\n3. Add task C (depends on B)\n\nNow we want to detect: if task D is added with `dependencies: [C]`, and somehow A depended on D, that would be a cycle. But since A has no dependencies on D (A was created first), no cycle exists -- which is correct.\n\nThe real limitation is that you can never create a true cycle in this system because dependencies must reference **already existing** tasks. A -> B -> C -> A is impossible to construct because when adding C with `dependencies: [B]`, A already exists without deps on C. The cycle detection is therefore never triggered in practice for the actual API. The test at line 331-360 acknowledges this:\n\n```typescript\nit('should reject circular dependencies', () => {\n  // ... test doesn't actually create a cycle\n});\nit('should detect indirect circular dependencies', () => {\n  // ... test doesn't actually test a cycle either\n});\n```\n\nBoth tests pass vacuously -- they never assert that a cycle is detected. The circular dependency detection code is dead code that can never fire given the current API design.\n\n**Severity:** Medium. The spec requires \"Circular dependencies (direct or indirect) must be detected and rejected at task-creation time.\" The detection code exists but is unreachable because the API cannot construct cycles. The tests do not verify this functionality. If the system were ever extended to allow modifying a task's dependencies, the detection would be needed.\n\n### H8. `getActiveCount()` scans the queue array, which excludes cancelled/completed tasks already spliced out\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 370-381\n\n```typescript\ngetActiveCount(queueName?: string): number {\n  const name = queueName ?? DEFAULT_QUEUE;\n  const queue = this.queues.get(name);\n  if (!queue) return 0;\n\n  let count = 0;\n  for (const id of queue) {\n    const task = this.tasks.get(id);\n    if (task && task.status === 'processing') count++;\n  }\n  return count;\n}\n```\n\nThis iterates over the queue array. However, tasks that were moved to the DLQ have been `splice`d out of the queue array (line 252). If a task is in `'processing'` status and has not been spliced out, it will be counted. But the real issue is: after `cancel()` for a processing task, the task is spliced out of the queue array but still has status `'processing'` at the point of cancellation -- wait, no, `cancel()` sets status to `'cancelled'` first (line 435), then splices. So after cancel, it would not be counted. This is fine.\n\nHowever, there is a subtle correctness issue with concurrency control: when `get()` checks `getActiveCount` (line 137), it only scans the current queue's array. But if a task is processing and then its ID is removed from the queue array (e.g., by some future code path), the concurrency slot would be silently freed. Currently, the only code path that removes processing tasks from the array is `cancel()`, which also changes status. So this is not a bug today but is fragile.\n\n**Severity:** Low. Not a current bug, but the architecture of counting active tasks by scanning the queue array rather than a dedicated counter is fragile.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM PRIORITY: Significant Design Issues\n\n### M1. Duplicated task construction code in `add()`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`, lines 80-127\n\nThe `add()` method has two nearly identical code blocks for constructing a task -- one for when dependencies exist and one for when they don't. The only difference is:\n- The dependency path pre-generates a UUID for cycle detection\n- The no-dependency path generates UUID inline\n\nThis can be consolidated into a single code path:\n\n```typescript\nconst taskId = randomUUID();\nif (dependencies.length > 0) {\n  this.detectCircularDeps(taskId, dependencies);\n}\nconst task: Task<T> = { id: taskId, /* ... */ dependencies: [...dependencies] };\n// ...\n```\n\n**Severity:** Medium. Code duplication increases maintenance burden and risk of divergence.\n\n### M2. Queue array grows unboundedly with completed/failed tasks\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/TaskQueue.ts`\n\nThe `queues` Map stores arrays of task IDs. When tasks are completed or failed (and retried), they remain